Real-World Example

Suppose you send an email from Gmail to a colleague.

Your email app sends the message using SMTP.
The recipient's mail server receives the message.
The recipient opens the email:
Using POP3, the email is downloaded to one device.
Using IMAP, the email stays on the server and appears on the phone, laptop, and tablet.

Linux Commands

Check if an SMTP server responds:

nc smtp.gmail.com 587

If nc (Netcat) is not installed:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install netcat-openbsd

Test SMTP with Telnet (if installed):

telnet smtp.gmail.com 587

View open TCP connections:

ss -t

Check DNS records (including mail-related records):

dig gmail.com

To query MX records specifically:

dig gmail.com MX

If dig is missing:

sudo apt install dnsutils
Common Email Ports
Protocol	Port	Secure Port
SMTP	25	465 / 587
POP3	110	995
IMAP	143	993


Advantages & Disadvantages
SMTP

Advantages
Reliable message delivery.
Widely supported.
Standard for sending email.

Disadvantages
Cannot retrieve email.
Requires additional protocols for receiving.
POP3

Advantages
Stores emails locally.
Simple to configure.
Good for a single-device setup.

Disadvantages
Poor synchronization.
Less suitable for modern multi-device use.
IMAP

Advantages
Synchronizes across devices.
Keeps emails on the server.
Ideal for smartphones, laptops, and tablets.

Disadvantages
Requires more server storage.
Depends on network connectivity for the best experience.


